Gwurf edition

>Who is /fat/ for?
For fatties who are working towards a better physique through meaningful hard-work, strategy, and dedication. This is not QTDDTOT, stick to questions on fat loss. Post height and weight when asking for advice.
Join our Fatty Contest: https://www.fattycontest.com/

>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).

>Now what?
Count calories, all of them.
Eat about 500-1000 less calories than your TDEE.
Buy scales, be accurate.
Learn to cook. Try to stick to lean protein and green vegetables.
Eat a lot of protein. 0.72g per lb of goal lean body mass.
Doing cardio, even just walking, will improve your health. There is no such thing as a healthy fat heart, but you can offset the risks.
Lifting weights will keep and gain muscle mass and burn fat much quicker. No lifting results in the body burning away muscle AND fat.
Drink more water.
Read the /fit/ sticky: https://liamrosen.com/fitness.html

>DON'T
Eat refined sugars, they're terrible for you regardless of calories.
Eat processed foods.
Drink your calories (alcohol, soda, starbucks).
Freak out over a weight loss stall. Plateaus can last up to three weeks.
"Reward" yourself. Cheat days cheat only yourself.

>Other resources:
Loose skin, gyno & stretch marks: https://weight-loss-side-effects.netlify.app/
Reddit wiki: https://www.reddit.com/r/loseit/wiki/faq

Started at 100kg around 3 months ago.
Fixed my diet starting from cutting coke and other sodas, stopped frying foods etc.
Later started lifting a bit (for chest mostly, once every 3rd day), and going for a long walks (12km +/-) pretty often.
Switched almost eclusively to natural foods that I cook myself, and drink only black coffe, tea (without sugar etc.), water. Once a week I have some kind of fast food, like kebab - still fit it in my kcal deficit though, no pigging out, or taking 3000kcal in a day.
I lost most of my fat, my face improved, I thought I had gyno for sure - today I am almost certainly sure it was just fat because they look normal (a bit puffy nipples but w/e).
I weighted myself today and saw 85kg on one scale, and 84.7 on another, (I am 198cm, 23 y.o.) this is insanely nice to see that I am making it. My goal now is to hit 80kg and go to get my bf% checked (there is a dietician near me that does first one for free), and figure out what to do then. I don't wanna go skelly mode, but I wanna be just slim with a subtle showing of muscles - then as I get older I plan to get more muscular.

The best feeling is wearing a shirt that was showing Your belly few months ago, and now it is hanging on You, when You put on pants and need to tighten Your belt so they don't fall off. I am intentionally pulling out old t-shirts and wearing them as a badge of honor because they fit me now.

Started translating on Upwork without officially registering for a business. Found bottom-feeding clients there, but I also came into contact there with some agencies that I still to this day continue working with.

All of the above in 2018. Went slow for two years, then met a domestic client (applied for a job interview, told them that I also offer translation services on a freelance basis, and now this client leaves me 50k EUR per year).

Registered for a business in January 2020. Fast forward to today, I have a full time in-house translator as an employee and on my way to complete my website and start officially as an agency (already work as an agency, as I subcontract 90% of work I undertake).

I wrote the above to give you some context. Now, regarding you:
Register yourself in Upwork and Proz.
Register to huge LSPs like Transperfect, Lionbridge & Welocalize.
Find, via Google maps, local agencies that might be looking for a translator. Even an in-house position, although not worthy money-wise, will leave you with a lot of experience.
Fake it till you make it. If you get offered a project and they ask you if you have relevant experience, if you trust that you know the subject (e.g., gaming/fitness), just say that you do have some, and if they ask for work samples, say that all your work is NDA-protected.
Also, when taking tests, be VERY FUCKING CAREFUL, because a 200-word test will either give you the chance of your life or block you from it.
Peace.

The thing with "Shitwork", which is shit, I agree, is that it is maybe the only place where you will get the chance to undertake work without credentials, simply because the people who offer work are looking to complete an one-time thing or are cheap fucks, or usually both.

ProZ is probably the most reputable site out there, being online since like 2000. Many agencies, during the application process, ask for your ProZ profile. However, I believe that in the next few years, LinkedIn will surpass them all, as I see more and more LinkedIn translation job posting, as well as many translation companies HR managers visiting my LinkedIn profile.

Also, if you want regular work, and you are not some kind of reputable individual translator, you will be working with agencies.

Forget, I repeat, FORGET, offering "easy" and "techie" payment solutions like bitcoin. 99.99% of agencies will want a legal invoice from you, so they can deduct your fees from their tax profits. This is industry standard, and pretty much applies to most service-based industries. Offering to be paid in Bitcoin only makes you look like some scammy, inexperienced and unprofessional kid.

And yes, the client usually sets the rules for that. Most US-based agencies work with Payoneer & PayPal, while European ones tend to prefer Bank Account Numbers (IBAN). Something like Transferwise is also possible.

- If you start to feel pain anywhere, stop and rest, then run a shorter distance next time or walk
- Don't worry about form, the human body knows how to run, just do what comes naturally
- Once you can comfortably run 6 miles/10km, start thinking about a goal in terms of race distance and time, and look for a training plan for that goal (see below for suggested plans)

Looking into there's a study that runners with the "inflexibility gene" (COL5A1) had slightly faster times during the running portion of a triathlon.
However a later study looking at the same gene didn't find any significant correlation between running economy and range of motion.
I'm a social scientist so I'm not sure I interpreted the study correctly so I'll link em so you can make your own assumptions.
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20798666/
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25188268/

Ultimately I think flexibility is good for general health and injury prevention, but so is stability and mobility.
You also shouldn't do static stretches before running (or lifting) but some dynamic warmups are a good idea.

>creation of plan

>repeat

>>69751994
I made odjakhuri and you can, too.

Ingredients:
1 kg pork neck
6 medium potatoes
3 onions
3 cloves of garlic
1 red bell pepper
2 hot peppers
500g tomato paste
spices
yoghurt
cilantro

1. Chop the pork neck into small pieces and fry it. No oil. Neck is quite fat, most of that fat will melt and be your base for the dish.
2. Add the chopped potatoes and fry them with meat.
3. When the potatoes are golden, throw in chopped onions, bell peppers, the hot peppers, and the crushed garlic.
4. Add the spices. Georgian svanetian salt and adjika if you can get these. If not, then add a lot of black pepper, herbs de Provence, lovage etc.
5. Throw in the tomato paste and simmer for 20-30 minutes.
6. Serve with a dollop of high-protein yoghurt and freshly chopped cilantro.

You'll love it.

>>69755074
If you're drinking enough that you have to ask the question, then you should just already consider it an addiction at this point, even if it's just the early stages of an addiction, and nip it in the bud before it gets worse. Honestly just stop drinking and smoking. All it takes is a bit of willpower and effort.

Drinking messes with your goals and even the slightest leeway you give yourself will set you down the wrong path, and the further down that path you go, the harder it is to come back. I stopped drinking for a few years and got to the best shape I had ever been in. Then I started drinking again, like you, I wasn't getting drunk but I was having a little bit of alcohol, a beer or two, maybe twice a week after work. That eventually turned into a habit and some weeks it would be five days out of seven. In the end it had a knock-on effect on my diet and sleep schedule, and I spent a ton of money that I otherwise would have saved, and overall just took a massive step backwards. All of that without ever actually getting drunk like you would expect an alcoholic to do.

Am I an alcoholic? Depends how you define it, I don't *need* alcohol to function but my relationship with alcohol has definitely been detrimental to my life, so I think it's safest to interpret addiction in the most extreme way so that you avoid all pitfalls - don't wait until you're getting plastered at midday to call yourself an alcoholic. When you drink little but often, the trap is that you know you should stop, but you convince yourself it's not so bad because your habit doesn't have the immediate life-ruining consequences that full-blown alcoholism does. So it's a slow descent into ruin and you don't notice it until it's too late.

tl;dr just stop drinking

>>69749205
the basic compound lifts are inferior. OHP is made infinitely safer and less injury prone by using neutral grip, bench press is made safer by doing dips, squat is made safer by doing split squats, and deadlift is made safer by doing RDLs.

All of these modifications reduce injury and in some cases offer more bang for your buck. You can realistically just do a bunch of split squats on leg day and call it a day since they work the entire leg. You're even getting a stretch in your achilles tendon. Neutral grip OHP prevents internal rotation of the humerus and removes some of the strain on the joint as you raise and lower the weight while also maintaining medial and anterior delt activation. Dips will work the entire shoulder girdle and will actually work your lats isometrically as you brace against the movement while also offering a better stretch on your pecs. RDLs will eccentrically load your posterior chain, which research is showing is better for muscle growth than concentric exercises

I got shat on for saying this before but I have a theory that every person has a maximum deadlift weight they can perform at with sloppy form without any damage or with only a little damage.

This makes sense because we all know there is a region in the lower back that has a certain capacity for bending and for ability to bear weight that can not go up infinitely. Sure if you were Zeus you could still pick the bar up in one hand, that's not how normal people's strength works.

So just because the pros don't like doing it doesn't mean it's a bad lift for regular people. The pros aren't going to be lifting 4 plates, they're going to be lifting 6+, and that's where it all starts breaking down for the pros. For normies, as long as you don't go much above 3-4 plate and you give some sort of effort to maintain form, there should be no problems.
